[node name="RichTextLabel" type="RichTextLabel" parent="CanvasLayer2/InfoPanel/MarginContainer/ScrollContainer/VBoxContainer" unique_id=1821922676]
layout_mode = 2
size_flags_horizontal = 3
size_flags_vertical = 3
focus_mode = 2
theme_override_font_sizes/normal_font_size = 20
bbcode_enabled = true
text = "[font_size=28]The Game of Life[/font_size]

The Game of Life is a cellular automaton devised by mathematician John Conway in 1970. Think of it as a living grid — every cell is either [b]alive[/b] or [b]dead[/b], and with each new generation, four simple rules are applied to every cell at the same time:

	- A living cell with fewer than [b]2[/b] neighbors dies from isolation.
	- A living cell with [b]2 or 3[/b] neighbors survives to the next generation.
	- A living cell with more than [b]3[/b] neighbors dies from overcrowding.
	- A dead cell with exactly [b]3[/b] neighbors becomes alive through reproduction.

That's it. From just these four rules, surprisingly complex behavior can emerge: stable structures, repeating oscillators, and even patterns that travel across the grid indefinitely.

[i][font_size=20]Why an aperiodic grid?[/font_size][/i]

On a standard square grid, every cell has exactly 8 neighbors. This uniformity is what makes classic Game of Life patterns so predictable and portable — a glider behaves the same no matter where you place it.

This grid is different. It is built from the [b]Einstein monotile[/b], nicknamed the \"hat,\" a 13-sided shape that tiles the plane without ever repeating. You can read about it in the 2023 paper by Smith et al. [url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.10798]here[/url].

Because the tiling never repeats, no two tiles share exactly the same neighborhood geometry. Depending on where it sits in the tiling, a cell can have either [b]6 or 7 neighbors[/b]. This subtle difference that changes how the rules play out locally. A pattern that oscillates in one region may stabilize, mutate, or collapse entirely if placed just a few tiles over.

This makes the aperiodic grid a genuinely different environment to explore. What survives here is largely an open question. I've already found several different structures that lead to periodic behavior. What can you find?

[font_size=20]A note on the grid[/font_size]

While the Einstein monotile can tile the plane infinitely in theory, this application uses a [b]finite grid[/b]. Cells near the boundary have fewer neighbors than they otherwise would, which may affect behavior near the edges.

[font_size=28]Controls[/font_size]

	- [b]Click[/b] — toggle a cell alive or dead
	- [b]Click and drag[/b] — paint cells like a brush
	- [b]Scroll wheel[/b] — zoom in and out
	- [b]Middle click drag[/b] — pan across the grid"
fit_content = true
vertical_alignment = 3
selection_enabled = true
script = ExtResource("10_fbb48")

